Note that $$
f(x) + f(y) = x^2 + 6x + y^2 + 6y + 2 = (x+3)^2 + (y+3)^2 -
16
$$and $$
f(x) - f(y) = x^2-y^2 + 6(x-y) = (x-y)(x+y+6).
$$The given conditions can be written as $$
(x+3)^2 + (y+3)^2 \le 16 \quad {\text{and}}\quad (x-y)(x+y+6) \le
0.
$$The first inequality describes the region on and inside the circle of radius 4 with center $(-3,-3)$. The second inequality can be rewritten as $$
(x-y \ge 0 \text{ and } x+y+6 \le 0) \quad \text{or} \quad (x-y
\le 0 \text{ and } x+y+6 \ge 0).
$$Each of these inequalities describes a half-plane bounded by a line that passes through $(-3,-3)$ and has slope 1 or $-1$. Thus, the set $R$ is the shaded region in the following diagram, and its area is half the area of the circle, which is $8\pi \approx 25.13.$, so the closest integer to $R$ is $\boxed{25}$. [asy]
fill((-3,1.2)..(0,0)--(-3,-3)--(-6,0)..cycle,gray(0.7));
fill((-3,-7.2)..(0,-6)--(-3,-3)--(-6,-6)..cycle,gray(0.7));
draw(Circle((-3,-3),4.2),linewidth(0.7));
for (int i=-7; i<3; ++i) {
draw((i,-0.2)--(i,0.2));
draw((-0.2,i)--(0.2,i));
}
draw((-7,1)--(1,-7),linewidth(1));
draw((1,1)--(-7,-7),linewidth(1));
draw((-8,0)--(3,0),Arrow);
draw((0,-8)--(0,3),Arrow);
label("$x$",(3,0),S);
label("$y$",(0,3),E);
label("-6",(-6,0),N);
label("-6",(0,-6),E);
label("$(-3,-3)$",(-3,-3),W);
[/asy]

We can write
\[f(x) = \sqrt{(x - 5)^2 + 3^2} - \sqrt{x^2 + 4}.\]Let $P = (x,0),$ $A = (5,3),$ and $B = (0,2).$  Then $f(x) = PA - PB.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.8 cm);

pair A, B, P;

A = (5,3);
B = (0,2);
P = (2.2,0);

draw((-0.5,0)--(5.5,0));
draw(A--P--B);

dot("$A = (5,3)$", A, NE);
dot("$B = (0,2)$", B, NW);
dot("$P = (x,0)$", P, S);
[/asy]

By the Triangle Inequality, $PA \le AB + PB,$ so
\[f(x) = PA - PB \le AB = \sqrt{26}.\]Equality occurs when $x = -10$ (which makes $P,$ $B,$ and $A$ collinear).

We can write
\begin{align*}
f(x) &= \sqrt{x^2 - 10x + 34} - \sqrt{x^2 + 4} \\
&= \frac{(\sqrt{x^2 - 10x + 34} - \sqrt{x^2 + 4})(\sqrt{x^2 - 10x + 34} + \sqrt{x^2 + 4})}{\sqrt{x^2 - 10x + 34} + \sqrt{x^2 + 4}} \\
&= \frac{(x^2 - 10x + 34) - (x^2 + 4)}{\sqrt{x^2 - 10x + 34} + \sqrt{x^2 + 4}} \\
&= \frac{-10x + 30}{\sqrt{x^2 - 10x + 34} + \sqrt{x^2 + 4}}.
\end{align*}If $x \le 3,$ then $f(x) \ge 0,$ so assume $x > 3,$ so
\[f(x) = -10 \cdot \frac{x - 3}{\sqrt{x^2 - 10x + 34} + \sqrt{x^2 + 4}}.\]If $3 < x \le 5,$ then
\[\frac{x - 3}{\sqrt{x^2 - 10x + 34} + \sqrt{x^2 + 4}} = \frac{x - 3}{\sqrt{(x - 5)^2 + 9} + \sqrt{x^2 + 4}} \le \frac{2}{3 + 4} = \frac{2}{7} < \frac{1}{2},\]so $f(x) > -5.$

If $x > 5,$ then
\begin{align*}
\frac{x - 3}{\sqrt{x^2 - 10x + 34} + \sqrt{x^2 + 4}} &= \frac{x - 3}{\sqrt{(x - 5)^2 + 9} + \sqrt{x^2 + 4}} \\
&< \frac{x - 3}{x - 5 + x} \\
&= \frac{x - 3}{2x - 5} \\
&< \frac{x - 3}{2x - 6} = \frac{1}{2},
\end{align*}so $f(x) > -5.$

Furthermore, as $x$ becomes very large,
\[\frac{x - 3}{\sqrt{x^2 - 10x + 34} + \sqrt{x^2 + 4}} = \frac{1 - \frac{3}{x}}{\sqrt{1 - \frac{10}{x} + \frac{34}{x^2}} + \sqrt{1 + \frac{4}{x^2}}}\]approaches $\frac{1}{1 + 1} = \frac{1}{2},$ so $f(x)$ approaches $-5.$

Therefore, the range of $f(x)$ is $\boxed{(-5,\sqrt{26}]}.$

The focus of the parabola $y^2 = 4ax$ is $F = (a,0),$ and the directrix is $x = -a.$  Then
\[PQ = PF + QF.\][asy]
unitsize(0.8 cm);

real y;
pair F, P, Q;

F = (1,0);

path parab = ((-4)^2/4,-4);

for (y = -4; y <= 4; y = y + 0.01) {
  parab = parab--(y^2/4,y);
}

P = intersectionpoint(F--(F + 5*(1,2)),parab);
Q = intersectionpoint(F--(F - 5*(1,2)),parab);

draw(parab,red);
draw((-2,0)--(4^2/4,0));
draw((0,-4)--(0,4));
draw((-1,-4)--(-1,4),dashed);
draw(P--Q);
draw(P--(-1,P.y));
draw(Q--(-1,Q.y));

label("$x = -a$", (-1,-4), S);

dot("$F$", F, SE);
dot("$P$", P, SE);
dot("$Q$", Q, S);
dot((-1,P.y));
dot((-1,Q.y));
[/asy]

Since $P$ lies on the parabola, $PF$ is equal to the distance from $P$ to the directrix, which is $x_1 + a.$  Similarly, $QF$ is equal to the distance from $Q$ to the directrix, which is $x_2 + a.$  Therefore,
\[PQ = x_1 + x_2 + 2a.\]Hence, $c_1 + c_2 + c_3 = 1 + 1 + 2 = \boxed{4}.$

